ion-victim-of-8-2-million-fraud-1.3710363|archivedate=August 8, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>August 8, 2016 AMA News Release {{cite web |url=https://news.ama.ab.ca/ama-statement/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-08-08 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006093008/https://news.ama.ab.ca/ama-statement/ |archivedate=October 6, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n|\n|Canada\n|Fraudulent invoices\n|-\n! {{Rh}} |[[Odebrecht]]\n|2016 <ref>{{cite news|title=Brazilian companies linked to Petrobras scandal plead guilty in US court|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/dec/21/brazil-petrobras-scandal-odebrecht-braskem-guilty|accessdate=21 December 2016|agency=The Guardian|date=December 20, 2016|language=English|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222052246/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/dec/21/brazil-petrobras-scandal-odebrecht-braskem-guilty|archivedate=December 22, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|\n|Brazil\n|Government bribes\n|-\n! {{Rh}} |[[1Malaysia Development Berhad]]\n|2018\n| [[Ernst & Young]], [[Deloitte]], [[KPMG]] <ref>{{cite news|title=Auditors highlight several critical areas in 1MDB's books|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/business/business-news/2014/04/22/auditors-highlight-several-critical-areas-in-its-books-and-reveal-more-funds/|accessdate=14 December 2018|agency=The Star|date=December 14, 2018|language=English}}</ref> \n|Malaysia\n|[[1Malaysia Development Berhad scandal|Fraud,  money laundering, abuse of political power, government bribes]]\n|}\n\n== Notable outcomes ==\nThe [[Enron scandal]] turned in to the indictment and criminal conviction of [[Big Four (audit firms)|Big Five auditor]] [[Arthur Andersen]] on June 15, 2002. Although the conviction was overturned on May 31, 2005, by the [[Supreme Court of the United States]], the firm ceased performing audits and split into multiple entities.<ref>{{Citation|title=Arthur Andersen|date=2019-01-09|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Arthur_Andersen&oldid=877519218|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2019-01-09}}</ref> The Enron scandal was defined as being one of the biggest audit failures of all time. The scandal included utilizing loopholes that were found within the [[Generally Accepted Accounting Principles (United States)|GAAP (General Accepted Accounting Principles)]]. For auditing a large-sized company such as Enron, the auditors were criticized for having brief meetings a few times a year that covered large amounts of material. By January 17, 2002, Enron decided to discontinue its business with Arthur Andersen, claiming they had failed in accounting advice and related documents.  Arthur Andersen was judged guilty of [[obstruction of justice]] for disposing of many emails and documents that were related to auditing Enron. Since the SEC is not allowed to accept audits from convicted felons, the firm was forced to give up its CPA licenses later in 2002, costing over 113,000 employees their jobs. Although the ruling was later overturned by the [[U.S. Supreme Court]], the once-proud firm's image was tarnished beyond repair, and it has not returned as a viable business even on a limited scale.\n\nOn July 9, 2002 [[George W. Bush]] gave a speech about recent accounting scandals that had been uncovered. In spite of its stern tone, the speech did not focus on establishing new policy, but instead focused on actually enforcing current laws, which include holding CEOs and directors personally responsible for accountancy fraud.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2002/07/20020709-4.html|title=Archived White House Website via George W. Bush Presidential Library and Museum - Text, audio and video of President Bush's speech - July 9, 2002|last=|first=|date=|website=Archived White House Website via George W. Bush Presidential Library and Museum|access-date=2019-01-09}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2002, [[WorldCom]] filed for bankruptcy protection in what was considered at the time as the largest corporate [[insolvency]] ever.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/unknown/2002/07/22/worldcoms-bankruptcy-mess|title=WorldCom's bankruptcy mess|date=2002-07-22|work=The Economist|access-date=2019-01-09|issn=0013-0613}}</ref>\n\nThese scandals reignited the debate over the relative merits of [[US GAAP]], which takes a \"rules-based\" approach to accounting, versus [[International Accounting Standards]] and [[UK GAAP]], which takes a \"principles-based\" approach.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uniassignment.com/essay-samples/accounting/the-principles-verse-rules-based-accounting-standard-debate-accounting-essay.php|title=The Principles Vs Rules Based Accounting Standard Debate|website=www.uniassignment.com|language=en|access-date=2019-01-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.investopedia.com/ask/answers/020915/do-all-countries-follow-same-gaap.asp|title=Do all countries follow the same GAAP?|last=Maverick|first=J. B.|website=Investopedia|access-date=2019-01-09}}</ref> The [[Financial Accounting Standards Board]] announced that it intends to introduce more principles-based standards. More radical means of [[accounting reform]] have been proposed, but so far have very little support. The debate itself, however, overlooks the difficulties of classifying any system of knowledge, including accounting, as rules-based or principles-based. This also led to the establishment of the [[Sarbanes\u2013Oxley Act|Sarbanes-Oxley Act]].\n\nOn a lighter note, the [[List of Ig Nobel Prize winners|2002]] [[Ig Nobel Prize]] in Economics went to the CEOs of those companies involved in the corporate accounting scandals of that year for \"...adapting the mathematical concept of [[imaginary number]]s for use in the business world.\"\n\nIn 2003, [[Nortel]] made a big contribution to this list of scandals by incorrectly reporting a one cent per share earnings directly after their massive [[layoff]] period. They used this money to pay the top 43 managers of the company. The [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission|SEC]] and the [[Ontario]] securities commission eventually settled civil action with Nortel. However, a separate civil action will be taken up against top Nortel executives including former CEO [[Frank A. Dunn]], Douglas C. Beatty, Michael J. Gollogly, and MaryAnne E. Pahapill and Hamilton. These proceedings have been postponed pending criminal proceedings in Canada, which opened in Toronto on January 12, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.canada.com/business/Nortel+trial+execs+raided+cookie+trigger+profit+driven+bonuses+court+told/6005109/story.html#ixzz1jx1lhaFw|title=canada.com - Page Not Found|publisher=|via=Canada.com}}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Crown lawyers at this fraud trial of three former Nortel Networks executives say the men defrauded the shareholders of Nortel of more than $5 million. According to the prosecutor this was accomplished by engineering a financial loss in 2002, and a profit in 2003 thereby triggering Return to Profit  bonuses of $70 million for top executives.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/story/2012/01/17/nortel-fraud-trial.html | work=CBC News | title=Nortel trial hears fraud allegations | date=January 17, 2012 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120121021144/http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/story/2012/01/17/nortel-fraud-trial.html | archivedate=January 21, 2012 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>http://news.businessweek.com/article.asp?documentKey=1376-LXR6J607SXKX01-6EE8N6QJ3AUEFIHKAV9DABRAOV{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=SheriffIsInTown |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thestar.com/business/article/1116710--nortel-trial-to-hear-defence-prosecution-arguments-tuesday | location=Toronto | work=The Star | first=Michael | last=Lewis | title=Nortel auditors pushed back against executives' scheme, prosecutor says | date=January 17, 2012 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120120013753/http://www.thestar.com/business/article/1116710--nortel-trial-to-hear-defence-prosecution-arguments-tuesday | archivedate=January 20, 2012 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thestar.com/business/article/1118602--nortel-trial-former-financial-director-saw-disconnect-between-stated-earnings-and-his-understanding-of-nortel-s-circumstances | location=Toronto | work=The Star | first=Michael | last=Lewis | title=Nortel trial: Former financial director saw disconnect between stated earnings and his understanding of Nortel's circumstances | date=January 20, 2012 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120123181314/http://www.thestar.com/business/article/1118602--nortel-trial-former-financial-director-saw-disconnect-between-stated-earnings-and-his-understanding-of-nortel-s-circumstances | archivedate=January 23, 2012 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/no-business-reason-to-release-nortel-reserves-court-told/article2309645/ |work=Globe and Mail |location=Toronto |title=No business reason to release Nortel reserves, court told |date=September 6, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304210618/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/no-business-reason-to-release-nortel-reserves-court-told/article2309645/ |archivedate=March 4, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In 2007, Dunn, Beatty, Gollogly, Pahapill, Hamilton, Craig A. Johnson, James B. Kinney, and Kenneth R.W. Taylor were charged with engaging in accounting fraud by \"...manipulating reserves to manage Nortel's earnings.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/litigation/litreleases/2007/lr20275.htm|title=SEC Charges Four Additional Former Officers of Nortel Networks Corporation in Financial Fraud Scheme: Lit. Rel. No. 20275 / September 12, 2007|website=www.sec.gov|access-date=2019-01-09}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, after a scandal on insurance and mutual funds the year before, [[American International Group|AIG]] was investigated for accounting fraud. The company already lost over $45 billion worth of market capitalization because of the scandal. Investigations also discovered over a $1 billion worth of errors in accounting transactions. The New York Attorney General's investigation led to a $1.6 billion fine for AIG and criminal charges for some of its executives.<ref>[https://finance.yahoo.com/news/AIG-executive-sentenced-to-4-apf-14168709.html Yahoo] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100105115438/https://finance.yahoo.com/news/AIG-executive-sentenced-to-4-apf-14168709.html |date=January 5, 2010 }}</ref> CEO [[Maurice R. Greenberg|Maurice R. \"Hank\" Greenberg]] was forced to step down and fought fraud charges until 2017, when the 91-year-old reached a $9.9 million settlement.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/14704060 |title=MSNBC |publisher=NBC News |accessdate=November 1, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Zuill |first=Lilla |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/ousiv/idUSTRE5222EV20090303 |title=Reuters |work=Reuters |accessdate=November 1, 2011 |date=March 3, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090307133921/http://www.reuters.com/article/ousiv/idUSTRE5222EV20090303 |archivedate=March 7, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Howard Smith, AIG's chief financial officer, also reached a settlement.\n\nWell before [[Bernard Madoff]]'s massive Ponzi scheme came to light, observers doubted whether his listed accounting firm \u2014 an unknown two-person firm in a rural area north of [[New York City]] \u2014 was competent to service a multibillion-dollar operation, especially since it had only one active accountant, [[David G. Friehling]].<ref>Fitzgerald, Jim. [http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/businesstechnology/2008533585_madoff18.html Madoff's financial empire audited by tiny firm: one guy] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219062906/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/businesstechnology/2008533585_madoff18.html |date=December 19, 2008 }}. [[Associated Press]] via [[Seattle Times]], December 18, 2008.</ref> Indeed, Friehling's practice was so small that for years, he operated out of his house; he only moved into an office when Madoff customers wanted to know more about who was auditing his accounts.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Madoff Chronicles|last=Ross|first=Brian|authorlink=Brian Ross (journalist)|publisher=[[Disney Publishing Worldwide|Kingswell]]|year=2015|isbn=9781401310295|url=https://archive.org/details/madoffchronicles00bria}}</ref> Ultimately, Friehling admitted to simply rubber-stamping at least 18 years' worth of Madoff's filings with the SEC. He also revealed that he continued to audit Madoff even though he had invested a substantial amount of money with him (Accountants are not allowed to audit broker-dealers with whom they're investing). He agreed to forfeit $3.18 million in accounting fees and withdrawals from his account with Madoff. His involvement makes the Madoff scheme the largest accounting fraud in world history.<ref name=\"Lawcom\">Hamblett, Mark. [http://www.law.com/jsp/article.jsp?id=1202435168711 Madoff's Accountant Acknowledges Guilt, Casts Himself as Victim]. [[New York Law Journal]], November 4, 2009.</ref>\n<!-- PLEASE RESPECT ALPHABETICAL ORDER -->\n\n==See also==\n* [[Accounting ethics]]\n*[[Creative accounting]]\n* [[Dot-com bubble]]\n* [[Financial crisis of 2007\u20132008]]\n* [[Forensic accounting]]\n* [[List of corporate collapses and scandals]]\n* [[Microcap stock fraud]]\n* [[Philosophy of accounting]]\n* [[Sarbanes\u2013Oxley Act]]\n* [[Savings and loan crisis]]\n* [[Securities fraud]]\n* [[Tobashi scheme]]\n*[[Repo 105]]\n* ''[[Vivien v. WorldCom]]''\n* [[White-collar crime]]\n*[[Hollywood accounting]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* John R. Emshwiller and Rebecca Smith, ''24 Days: How Two Wall Street Journal Reporters Uncovered the Lies that Destroyed Faith in Corporate America'' or ''Infectious Greed'', HarperInformation, 2003, {{ISBN|0-06-052073-6}}\n* [http://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=337280 Lawrence A. Cunningham, The Sarbanes-Oxley Yawn: Heavy Rhetoric, Light Reform (And It Might Just Work)]\n* Zabihollah Rezaee, Financial Statement Fraud: Prevention and Detection, Wiley 2002.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.sec.gov/ U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission website]\n* [https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=1146373 U.S. President Bush's speech, 2002-07-09] [[NPR]] report (audio recording)\n* [http://www.accountingtoday.com/news/GMI-Warns-Accounting-Risks-40-Companies-64802-1.html \"GMI Warns of Accounting Risks at 40 Companies\"], [[Accounting Today]], November 27, 2012\n* [http://www.businessinsider.com/corporate-fraud-red-flags-2013-6 \"The Impact of Fraud on Shareholder Value\"], [[Business Insider]], June 18, 2013\n{{Corporate scandals}}\n{{Aspects of corporations}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Accounting Scandals}}\n[[Category:Commercial crimes]]\n[[Category:Corporate scandals]]\n[[Category:Political corruption]]\n[[Category:Accounting scandals| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Scandal arising from the disclosure of financial misdeeds}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2012}}\n'''Accounting scandals''' are [[corporate abuse|business scandal]]s which arise from intentional manipulation of [[financial statement]]s with the disclosure of financial misdeeds by trusted [[executive (management)|executives]] of corporations or governments. Such misdeeds typically involve complex methods for misusing or misdirecting funds, overstating [[revenues]], understating expenses, overstating<ref>In Italian law the phrase \"still subject to evaluation\" now refers to material facts that are untrue: it was a clarification for \"informations\", but totally inconsistent with the \"facts\" reported in accounting documents: {{cite journal|last1=Buonomo|first1=Giampiero|title=Diritto societario: chiusa la discussione, approvazione a fine mese|journal=Diritto&Giustizia Edizione Online|date=2001|url=https://www.questia.com/projects#!/project/89309129|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160324160801/https://www.questia.com/projects#!/project/89309129|archivedate=March 24, 2016|df=mdy-all}} {{Subscription required |via=[[Questia]]}}</ref> the value of corporate assets, or underreporting the existence of [[liability (financial accounting)|liabilities]] (this can be done either manually, or by the means of [[deep learning]]<ref>{{Cite arXiv|title=Adversarial Learning of Deepfakes in Accounting|last=Schreyer|first=Marco|date=2019-10-09|eprint=1910.03810|class=cs.LG}}</ref>). It involves an employee, account, or corporation itself and is misleading to investors and [[shareholder]]s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.investopedia.com/ask/answers/032715/what-accounting-fraud.asp|title=What is accounting fraud?|last=Nickolas|first=Steven|date=2015-03-27|work=Investopedia|access-date=2017-03-19|language=en-US|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170320145307/http://www.investopedia.com/ask/answers/032715/what-accounting-fraud.asp|archivedate=March 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThis type of \"[[creative accounting]]\" can amount to [[fraud]], and investigations are typically launched by government [[Regulation|oversight]] agencies, such as the [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission|Securities and Exchange Commission]] (SEC) in the United States. Employees who commit accounting fraud at the request of their employers are subject to personal criminal prosecution.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.businessdictionary.com/definition/accounting-fraud.html|title=What is accounting fraud? definition and meaning|website=BusinessDictionary.com|language=en|access-date=2017-03-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170320144730/http://www.businessdictionary.com/definition/accounting-fraud.html|archivedate=March 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Two types of fraud ==\n\n=== Misappropriation of assets ===\n\nMisappropriation of assets \u2014 often called defalcation or employee fraud \u2014 occurs when an employee steals a company's asset, whether those assets are of monetary or physical nature. Typically, assets stolen are cash, or cash equivalents, and company data or [[intellectual property]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.actionfraud.police.uk/fraud_protection/asset_misappropriation|title=Asset misappropriation fraud|last=Anonymous|date=2010-01-25|work=Action Fraud|access-date=2017-03-19|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170320143735/http://www.actionfraud.police.uk/fraud_protection/asset_misappropriation|archivedate=March 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> However, misappropriation of assets also includes taking inventory out of a facility or using company assets for personal purpose without authorization. Company assets include everything from office supplies and inventory to intellectual property.\n\n=== Fraudulent financial reporting ===\n\nFraudulent financial reporting is also known as earnings management fraud. In this context, management intentionally manipulates accounting policies or accounting estimates to improve financial statements. Public and private corporations commit fraudulent financial reporting to secure investor interest or obtain bank approvals for financing, as justifications for bonuses or increased salaries or to meet expectations of shareholders.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://smallbusiness.chron.com/financial-statement-fraud-57182.html|title=What Is Financial Statement Fraud?|access-date=2017-03-20|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170320233602/http://smallbusiness.chron.com/financial-statement-fraud-57182.html|archivedate=March 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The Securities and Exchange Commission has brought enforcement actions against corporations for many types of fraudulent financial reporting, including improper revenue recognition, period-end stuffing, fraudulent post-closing entries, improper asset valuations, and misleading non-GAAP financial measures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fraud-magazine.com/article.aspx?id=4294994026|title=When do non-GAAP metrics become fraudulent publicity?|website=www.fraud-magazine.com|access-date=2019-01-09}}</ref>\n\n== The fraud triangle ==\nThe fraud triangle is a model for explaining the factors that cause someone to commit fraudulent behaviors in accounting. It consists of three components, which together, lead to fraudulent behavior:\n* Incentives/ Pressure: Management or other employees have incentives or pressures to commit fraud.\n* Opportunities: Circumstances provide opportunities for management or employees to commit fraud.\n* Attitudes/rationalization: An attitude, character, or set of ethical values exists that allows management or employees to commit a dishonest act, or they are in an environment that imposes sufficient pressure that causes them to rationalize committing a dishonest act.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Auditing and Assurance Services|last=Alvin|first=Aren|publisher=Pearson|year=2016|isbn=978-0134065823|location=|pages=299}}</ref>\n'''Incentives/pressures:''' A common incentive for companies to manipulate [[financial statement]] is a decline in the company's financial prospects. Companies may also manipulate earnings to meet analysts' forecasts or benchmarks such as prior-year earnings to: meet [[debt covenant]] restrictions, achieve a bonus target based on earnings, or artificially inflate stock prices. As for [[misappropriation of assets]], financial pressures are a common incentive for employees. Employees with excessive financial obligations, or those with substance abuse or gambling problems may steal to meet their personal needs.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Auditing and Assurance Services|last=Aren|first=Alvin|publisher=Pearson|year=2016|isbn=978-0134065823|location=New York|pages=300}}</ref>\n\n'''Opportunities:''' Although the financial statements of all companies are potentially subject to manipulation, the risk is greater for companies in industries where significant judgments and accounting estimates are involved. Turnover in accounting personnel or other deficiencies in accounting and information processes can create an opportunity for misstatement. As for misappropriation of assets, opportunities are greater in companies with accessible cash or with inventory or other valuable assets, especially if the assets are small or easily removed. A lack of controls over payments to vendors or payroll systems, can allow employees to create fictitious vendors or employees and bill the company for services or time.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Auditing and Assurance Services|last=Aren|first=Alvin|publisher=Pearson|year=2016|isbn=978-0134065823|location=New York|pages=301}}</ref>\n\n'''Attitudes/rationalization:''' The attitude of top management toward financial reporting is a critical risk factor in assessing the likelihood of fraudulent financial statements. If the CEO or other top managers display a significant disregard for the financial reporting process, such as consistently issuing overly optimistic forecasts, or they are overly concerned about the meeting analysts' earnings forecast, fraudulent [[financial reporting]] is more likely. Similarly, for misappropriation of assets, if management cheats customers through overcharging for goods or engaging in high-pressure sales tactics, employees may feel that it is acceptable for them to behave in the same fashion.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Auditing and Assurance Services|last=Aren|first=Alvin|publisher=Pearson|year=2016|isbn=978-0134065823|location=New York|pages=302}}</ref>\n\n==Causes==\n{{POV section|date=January 2014}}\nA weak internal control is an opportunity for a fraudster. Fraud is not an accounting problem; it is a social phenomenon. If you strip economic crime of its multitudinous variations, there are but three ways a victim can be unlawfully separated from money: by force, stealth or trickery.<ref>Wells, Joseph T. \"New Approaches to Fraud Deterrence.\" Business Credit 107.2 (2005): 33-6. ProQuest. Web. 31 Jan. 2018.</ref> Lack of transparency in financial transactions is an ideal method to hide a fraud. Poor management information where a company's management system does not produce results that are timely, accurate, sufficiently detailed and relevant. In such case, the warning signal of fraud such as ongoing theft from bank account can be obscured. Lack of an independent audit department within the company is also a sign of weak internal control. Poor accounting practice is also part of a weak internal control. An example of poor accounting practice is failure to make monthly reconciliation of bank account.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2012/09/14/top-10-reasons-frauds-occur-3817555/|title=Top 10 reasons why frauds occur|last=Frost|first=Ken|date=2012-09-14|website=Metro|access-date=2017-03-20|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170506185211/http://metro.co.uk/2012/09/14/top-10-reasons-frauds-occur-3817555/|archivedate=May 6, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nA top executive can reduce the price of his/her company's stock easily due to [[information asymmetry]]. The executive can accelerate accounting of expected expenses, delay accounting of expected revenue, engage in [[off balance sheet]] transactions to make the company's profitability appear temporarily poorer, or simply promote and report severely conservative (e.g. pessimistic) estimates of future earnings. Such seemingly adverse earnings news will be likely to (at least temporarily) reduce share price. (This is again due to [[information asymmetries]] since it is more common for top executives to do everything they can to [[window dress]] their company's earnings forecasts.\n\nTop managers tend to share price to make a company an easier [[takeover]] target. When the company gets bought out (or taken private) \u2013 at a dramatically lower price \u2013 the takeover artist gains a windfall from the former top executive's actions to surreptitiously reduce share price. This can represent tens of billions of dollars (questionably) transferred from previous shareholders to the takeover artist. The former top executive is then rewarded with a [[golden handshake]] for presiding over the [[firesale]] that can sometimes be in the hundreds of millions of dollars for one or two years of work.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/challenging-times-crisis-hit-cosalt/story-14389742-detail/story.html|title=Challenging times for crisis-hit Cosalt|date=2012-01-11|work=Grimsby Telegraph|access-date=2017-04-09|language=en}}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nSimilar issues occur when a publicly held asset or non-profit organization undergoes [[privatization]]. Top executives often reap tremendous monetary benefits when a government-owned or non-profit entity is sold to private hands. Just as in the example above, they can facilitate this process by making the entity appear to be in financial crisis \u2013 this reduces the sale price (to the profit of the purchaser), and makes non-profits and governments more likely to sell. It can also contribute to a public perception that private entities are more efficiently run, thereby reinforcing the political will to sell off public assets. Again, due to [[asymmetric information]], policy makers and the general public see a government-owned firm that was a financial 'disaster' \u2013 miraculously turned around by the private sector (and typically resold) within a few years. Under the Special Plea in Fraud statute, \u201cthe government must \u2018establish by clear and convincing evidence that the contractor knew that its submitted claims were false, and that it intended to defraud the government by submitting those claims.\u2019\u201d Mere negligence, inconsistency, or discrepancies are not actionable under the Special Plea in Fraud statute.<ref>Horan, Jack. \"Fraud is here, Fraud is there, but is Fraud Everywhere?\" Contract Management 01 2016: 64,65,67-69. ProQuest. Web. 31 Jan. 2018 .</ref>\n\nNot all accounting scandals are caused by top executives. The proceedings can take so long to come to trial that one executive saw the charges against him dismissed.<ref>Gray, John. \"CURTAIN RAISER.\" Canadian Business May 12, 2008: 61-4. ProQuest. Web. 31 Jan. 2018 .</ref> Often managers and employees are pressured or willingly alter financial statements for the personal benefit of the individuals over the company. [[Opportunism|Managerial opportunism]] plays a large role in these scandals. For example, managers who would be compensated more for short-term results would report inaccurate information, since short-term benefits outweigh the long-term ones such as pension obligations.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Cunningham|first=Lawrence|title=The Appeal and Limits of Internal Controls to Fight Fraud, Terrorism, Other Ills|date=September 12, 2003|page=18}}</ref>\n\n==List of biggest accounting scandals==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Company\n! Year\n! Audit Firm\n! Country\n! Notes\n|-\n! {{Rh}} |[[Ultramares Corp. v. Touche|Fred Stern & Company]]\n|1925\n|Touche, Niven & Co.\n|United States\n|\n|-\n! {{Rh}} |[[Clarence Hatry|Hatry Group]]\n|1929\n|\n|United Kingdom\n|\n|-\n! {{Rh}} |[[Royal Mail Case|Royal Mail Steam Packet Company]]\n|1931\n|\n|United Kingdom\n|\n|-\n! {{Rh}} |[[Interstate Hosiery Mills]]\n|1937\n|Homes and Davis\n|United States\n|\n|-\n! {{Rh}} |[[McKesson & Robbins scandal (1938)|McKesson & Robbins, Inc.]]\n|1938\n|Price, Waterhouse & Co.\n|United States\n|\n|-\n! {{Rh}} |Yale Express System\n|1965<ref>John Z. Szabo, Licenses\u2014Accountants' Liability\u2014Duty to Disclose [Fisher v. Kletz, 266 F. Supp. 180 (S.D.N.Y. 1967)], 19 Case Western Reserve Law Review p387 (1968){{cite web |url=h