2394|title=Penn West to restate results after accounting irregularities|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150919002436/http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/penn-west-to-restate-results-after-accounting-irregularities-1.2722394|archivedate=September 19, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|[[KPMG]]\n|Canada\n|Overstated profits\n|-\n! {{Rh}} |[[Pescanova]]                                 \n|2013\n|[[BDO Global|BDO Spain]]\n|Spain\n|Understated debt, Fraudulent invoices, Falsified accounts\n|-\n! {{Rh}} |[[Petrobras]]\n|2014 <ref>{{cite news|title=Operation Car Wash: Is this the biggest corruption scandal in history?|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/jun/01/brazil-operation-car-wash-is-this-the-biggest-corruption-scandal-in-history|accessdate=15 February 2019|agency=The Guardian|date=June 1, 2017|language=English|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190213235029/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/jun/01/brazil-operation-car-wash-is-this-the-biggest-corruption-scandal-in-history|archivedate=February 13, 2019|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|[[PricewaterhouseCoopers]]\n|Brazil\n|Government bribes, Misappropriation, Money laundering\n|-\n|'''Tesco'''\n|2014<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2019/01/23/former-tesco-executive-carl-rogberg-cleared-fraud-charges/|title=Full details of \u00a3326m Tesco accounting scandal revealed after Carl Rogberg is acquitted|last=Armstrong|first=Ashley|date=2019-01-23|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2019-11-20|last2=Torrance|first2=Jack|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n|[[PricewaterhouseCoopers]]\n|UK\n|Revenue recognition\n|-\n! {{Rh}} |[[Toshiba]]\n|2015<ref>{{cite news|last=Irvine|first=Julia|title=Toshiba profit overstated by \u00a3738m.|url=http://economia.icaew.com/news/july-2015/toshiba-profit-overstated-by-738m|date=July 21, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150726004053/http://economia.icaew.com/news/july-2015/toshiba-profit-overstated-by-738m|archivedate=July 26, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|[[Ernst & Young]]\n|Japan\n|Overstated profits\n|-\n! {{Rh}} |[[Valeant Pharmaceuticals]]\n|2015 <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/29/business/dealbook/valeants-accounting-error-a-warning-sign-of-bigger-problems.html?_r=0|title=Valeant's Accounting Error a Warning Sign of Bigger Problems|first=Peter|last=Eavis|date=March 28, 2016|via=www.nytimes.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201061617/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/29/business/dealbook/valeants-accounting-error-a-warning-sign-of-bigger-problems.html?_r=0|archivedate=December 1, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|[[PricewaterhouseCoopers]]\n|Canada\n|Overstated revenues\n|-\n! {{Rh}} |[[Alberta Motor Association]]\n|2016 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/lawsuit-alleges-alberta-motor-association-victim-of-8-2-million-fraud-1.3710363|title=Vice-president at Alberta Motor Association fired over alleged fake invoice scheme|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808112750/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/lawsuit-alleges-alberta-motor-association-victim-of-8-2-million-fraud-1.3710363|archivedate=August 8, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>August 8, 2016 AMA News Release {{cite web |url=https://news.ama.ab.ca/ama-statement/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-08-08 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006093008/https://news.ama.ab.ca/ama-statement/ |archivedate=October 6, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n|\n|Canada\n|Fraudulent invoices\n|-\n! {{Rh}} |[[Odebrecht]]\n|2016 <ref>{{cite news|title=Brazilian companies linked to Petrobras scandal plead guilty in US court|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/dec/21/brazil-petrobras-scandal-odebrecht-braskem-guilty|accessdate=21 December 2016|agency=The Guardian|date=December 20, 2016|language=English|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222052246/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/dec/21/brazil-petrobras-scandal-odebrecht-braskem-guilty|archivedate=December 22, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|\n|Brazil\n|Government bribes\n|-\n! {{Rh}} |[[1Malaysia Development Berhad]]\n|2018\n| [[Ernst & Young]], [[Deloitte]], [[KPMG]] <ref>{{cite news|title=Auditors highlight several critical areas in 1MDB's books|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/business/business-news/2014/04/22/auditors-highlight-several-critical-areas-in-its-books-and-reveal-more-funds/|accessdate=14 December 2018|agency=The Star|date=December 14, 2018|language=English}}</ref> \n|Malaysia\n|[[1Malaysia_Development_Berhad_scandal|Fraud,  money laundering, abuse of political power, government bribes]]\n|}\n\n== Notable outcomes ==\nThe [[Enron scandal]] turned in to the indictment and criminal conviction of [[Big Four (audit firms)|Big Five auditor]] [[Arthur Andersen]] on June 15, 2002. Although the conviction was overturned on May 31, 2005, by the [[Supreme Court of the United States]], the firm ceased performing audits and split into multiple entities.<ref>{{Citation|title=Arthur Andersen|date=2019-01-09|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Arthur_Andersen&oldid=877519218|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2019-01-09}}</ref> The Enron scandal was defined as being one of the biggest audit failures of all time. The scandal included utilizing loopholes that were found within the [[Generally Accepted Accounting Principles (United States)|GAAP (General Accepted Accounting Principles)]]. For auditing a large-sized company such as Enron, the auditors were criticized for having brief meetings a few times a year that covered large amounts of material. By January 17, 2002, Enron decided to discontinue its business with Arthur Andersen, claiming they had failed in accounting advice and related documents.  Arthur Andersen was judged guilty of [[obstruction of justice]] for disposing of many emails and documents that were related to auditing Enron. Since the SEC is not allowed to accept audits from convicted felons, the firm was forced to give up its CPA licenses later in 2002, costing over 113,000 employees their jobs. Although the ruling was later overturned by the [[U.S. Supreme Court]], the once-proud firm's image was tarnished beyond repair, and it has not returned as a viable business even on a limited scale.\n\nOn July 9, 2002 [[George W. Bush]] gave a speech about recent accounting scandals that had been uncovered. In spite of its stern tone, the speech did not focus on establishing new policy, but instead focused on actually enforcing current laws, which include holding CEOs and directors personally responsible for accountancy fraud.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2002/07/20020709-4.html|title=Archived White House Website via George W. Bush Presidential Library and Museum - Text, audio and video of President Bush's speech - July 9, 2002|last=|first=|date=|website=Archived White House Website via George W. Bush Presidential Library and Museum|access-date=2019-01-09}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2002, [[WorldCom]] filed for bankruptcy protection in what was considered at the time as the largest corporate [[insolvency]] ever.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/unknown/2002/07/22/worldcoms-bankruptcy-mess|title=WorldCom's bankruptcy mess|date=2002-07-22|work=The Economist|access-date=2019-01-09|issn=0013-0613}}</ref>\n\nThese scandals reignited the debate over the relative merits of [[US GAAP]], which takes a \"rules-based\" approach to accounting, versus [[International Accounting Standards]] and [[UK GAAP]], which takes a \"principles-based\" approach.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uniassignment.com/essay-samples/accounting/the-principles-verse-rules-based-accounting-standard-debate-accounting-essay.php|title=The Principles Vs Rules Based Accounting Standard Debate|website=www.uniassignment.com|language=en|access-date=2019-01-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.investopedia.com/ask/answers/020915/do-all-countries-follow-same-gaap.asp|title=Do all countries follow the same GAAP?|last=Maverick|first=J. B.|website=Investopedia|access-date=2019-01-09}}</ref> The [[Financial Accounting Standards Board]] announced that it intends to introduce more principles-based standards. More radical means of [[accounting reform]] have been proposed, but so far have very little support. The debate itself, however, overlooks the difficulties of classifying any system of knowledge, including accounting, as rules-based or principles-based. This also led to the establishment of the [[Sarbanes\u2013Oxley Act|Sarbanes-Oxley Act]].\n\nOn a lighter note, the [[List of Ig Nobel Prize winners|2002]] [[Ig Nobel Prize]] in Economics went to the CEOs of those companies involved in the corporate accounting scandals of that year for \"...adapting the mathematical concept of [[imaginary number]]s for use in the business world.\"\n\nIn 2003, [[Nortel]] made a big contribution to this list of scandals by incorrectly reporting a one cent per share earnings directly after their massive [[layoff]] period. They used this money to pay the top 43 managers of the company. The [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission|SEC]] and the [[Ontario]] securities commission eventually settled civil action with Nortel. However, a separate civil action will be taken up against top Nortel executives including former CEO [[Frank A. Dunn]], Douglas C. Beatty, Michael J. Gollogly, and MaryAnne E. Pahapill and Hamilton. These proceedings have been postponed pending criminal proceedings in Canada, which opened in Toronto on January 12, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.canada.com/business/Nortel+trial+execs+raided+cookie+trigger+profit+driven+bonuses+court+told/6005109/story.html#ixzz1jx1lhaFw|title=canada.com - Page Not Found|publisher=|via=Canada.com}}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Crown lawyers at this fraud trial of three former Nortel Networks executives say the men defrauded the shareholders of Nortel of more than $5 million. According to the prosecutor this was accomplished by engineering a financial loss in 2002, and a profit in 2003 thereby triggering Return to Profit  bonuses of $70 million for top executives.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/story/2012/01/17/nortel-fraud-trial.html | work=CBC News | title=Nortel trial hears fraud allegations | date=January 17, 2012 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120121021144/http://www.cbc.ca/news/business/story/2012/01/17/nortel-fraud-trial.html | archivedate=January 21, 2012 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>http://news.businessweek.com/article.asp?documentKey=1376-LXR6J607SXKX01-6EE8N6QJ3AUEFIHKAV9DABRAOV{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=SheriffIsInTown |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thestar.com/business/article/1116710--nortel-trial-to-hear-defence-prosecution-arguments-tuesday | location=Toronto | work=The Star | first=Michael | last=Lewis | title=Nortel auditors pushed back against executives' scheme, prosecutor says | date=January 17, 2012 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120120013753/http://www.thestar.com/business/article/1116710--nortel-trial-to-hear-defence-prosecution-arguments-tuesday | archivedate=January 20, 2012 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thestar.com/business/article/1118602--nortel-trial-former-financial-director-saw-disconnect-between-stated-earnings-and-his-understanding-of-nortel-s-circumstances | location=Toronto | work=The Star | first=Michael | last=Lewis | title=Nortel trial: Former financial director saw disconnect between stated earnings and his understanding of Nortel's circumstances | date=January 20, 2012 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120123181314/http://www.thestar.com/business/article/1118602--nortel-trial-former-financial-director-saw-disconnect-between-stated-earnings-and-his-understanding-of-nortel-s-circumstances | archivedate=January 23, 2012 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/no-business-reason-to-release-nortel-reserves-court-told/article2309645/ |work=Globe and Mail |location=Toronto |title=No business reason to release Nortel reserves, court told |date=September 6, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304210618/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/no-business-reason-to-release-nortel-reserves-court-told/article2309645/ |archivedate=March 4, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In 2007, Dunn, Beatty, Gollogly, Pahapill, Hamilton, Craig A. Johnson, James B. Kinney, and Kenneth R.W. Taylor were charged with engaging in accounting fraud by \"...manipulating reserves to manage Nortel's earnings.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/litigation/litreleases/2007/lr20275.htm|title=SEC Charges Four Additional Former Officers of Nortel Networks Corporation in Financial Fraud Scheme: Lit. Rel. No. 20275 / September 12, 2007|website=www.sec.gov|access-date=2019-01-09}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, after a scandal on insurance and mutual funds the year before, [[American International Group|AIG]] was investigated for accounting fraud. The company already lost over $45 billion worth of market capitalization because of the scandal. Investigations also discovered over a $1 billion worth of errors in accounting transactions. The New York Attorney General's investigation led to a $1.6 billion fine for AIG and criminal charges for some of its executives.<ref>[https://finance.yahoo.com/news/AIG-executive-sentenced-to-4-apf-14168709.html Yahoo] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100105115438/https://finance.yahoo.com/news/AIG-executive-sentenced-to-4-apf-14168709.html |date=January 5, 2010 }}</ref> CEO [[Maurice R. Greenberg|Maurice R. \"Hank\" Greenberg]] was forced to step down and fought fraud charges until 2017, when the 91-year-old reached a $9.9 million settlement.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/14704060 |title=MSNBC |publisher=NBC News |accessdate=November 1, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Zuill |first=Lilla |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/ousiv/idUSTRE5222EV20090303 |title=Reuters |work=Reuters |accessdate=November 1, 2011 |date=March 3, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090307133921/http://www.reuters.com/article/ousiv/idUSTRE5222EV20090303 |archivedate=March 7, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Howard Smith, AIG's chief financial officer, also reached a settlement.\n\nWell before [[Bernard Madoff]]'s massive Ponzi scheme came to light, observers doubted whether his listed accounting firm \u2014 an unknown two-person firm in a rural area north of [[New York City]] \u2014 was competent to service a multibillion-dollar operation, especially since it had only one active accountant, [[David G. Friehling]].<ref>Fitzgerald, Jim. [http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/businesstechnology/2008533585_madoff18.html Madoff's financial empire audited by tiny firm: one guy] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219062906/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/businesstechnology/2008533585_madoff18.html |date=December 19, 2008 }}. [[Associated Press]] via [[Seattle Times]], December 18, 2008.</ref> Indeed, Friehling's practice was so small that for years, he operated out of his house; he only moved into an office when Madoff customers wanted to know more about who was auditing his accounts.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Madoff Chronicles|last=Ross|first=Brian|authorlink=Brian Ross (journalist)|publisher=[[Disney Publishing Worldwide|Kingswell]]|year=2015|isbn=9781401310295|url=https://archive.org/details/madoffchronicles00bria}}</ref> Ultimately, Friehling admitted to simply rubber-stamping at least 18 years' worth of Madoff's filings with the SEC. He also revealed that he continued to audit Madoff even though he had invested a substantial amount of money with him (Accountants are not allowed to audit broker-dealers with whom they're investing). He agreed to forfeit $3.18 million in accounting fees and withdrawals from his account with Madoff. His involvement makes the Madoff scheme the largest accounting fraud in world history.<ref name=\"Lawcom\">Hamblett, Mark. [http://www.law.com/jsp/article.jsp?id=1202435168711 Madoff's Accountant Acknowledges Guilt, Casts Himself as Victim]. [[New York Law Journal]], November 4, 2009.</ref>\n<!-- PLEASE RESPECT ALPHABETICAL ORDER -->\n\n==See also==\n* [[Accounting ethics]]\n*[[Creative accounting]]\n* [[Dot-com bubble]]\n* [[Financial crisis of 2007\u20132008]]\n* [[Forensic accounting]]\n* [[List of corporate collapses and scandals]]\n* [[Microcap stock fraud]]\n* [[Philosophy of accounting]]\n* [[Sarbanes\u2013Oxley Act]]\n* [[Savings and loan crisis]]\n* [[Securities fraud]]\n* [[Tobashi scheme]]\n*[[Repo 105]]\n* ''[[Vivien v. WorldCom]]''\n* [[White-collar crime]]\n*[[Hollywood accounting]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* John R. Emshwiller and Rebecca Smith, ''24 Days: How Two Wall Street Journal Reporters Uncovered the Lies that Destroyed Faith in Corporate America'' or ''Infectious Greed'', HarperInformation, 2003, {{ISBN|0-06-052073-6}}\n* [http://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=337280 Lawrence A. Cunningham, The Sarbanes-Oxley Yawn: Heavy Rhetoric, Light Reform (And It Might Just Work)]\n* Zabihollah Rezaee, Financial Statement Fraud: Prevention and Detection, Wiley 2002.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.sec.gov/ U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission website]\n* [https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=1146373 U.S. President Bush's speech, 2002-07-09] [[NPR]] report (audio recording)\n* [http://www.accountingtoday.com/news/GMI-Warns-Accounting-Risks-40-Companies-64802-1.html \"GMI Warns of Accounting Risks at 40 Companies\"], [[Accounting Today]], November 27, 2012\n* [http://www.businessinsider.com/corporate-fraud-red-flags-2013-6 \"The Impact of Fraud on Shareholder Value\"], [[Business Insider]], June 18, 2013\n{{Corporate scandals}}\n{{Aspects of corporations}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Accounting Scandals}}\n[[Category:Commercial crimes]]\n[[Category:Corporate scandals]]\n[[Category:Political corruption]]\n[[Category:Accounting scandals| ]]\n", "name_user": "Kaltenmeyer", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eList of biggest accounting scandals:clean up, replaced: a $80 \u2192  an $80", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accounting_scandals"}
